Task 3: Recoding and variable manipulation

  1. Deal with missing values, which are currently coded as -99.
for (x in c("total_enroll","per_free_lunch","per_reduced_lunch","per_lep","mean_ela_score","mean_math_score")){
nys_schools[[x]][nys_schools[[x]] == -99] <-mean(nys_schools[[x]][nys_schools[[x]] != -99])}
  1. Create a categorical variable that groups counties into high, medium, and low poverty groups. Decide how you want to split up the groups and briefly explain your decision.

#sort(table(nys_acs$median_household_income))

quantiles <- quantile(nys_acs$county_per_poverty, probs =seq(0, 1, by = 1/3))

nys_acs$proverty_level<-cut(nys_acs$county_per_poverty,breaks=quantiles, labels=c("high","medium","low"),include.lowest = 'True')
  1. The tests that the NYS Department of Education administers changes from time to time, so scale scores are not directly comparable year-to-year. Create a new variable that is the standardized z-score for math and English Language Arts (ELA) for each year (hint: group by year and use the scale() function)
scores_std <-nys_schools %>%
  select(year, contains("score")) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    ela_mean = mean(mean_ela_score, na.rm = TRUE),
    math_mean = mean(mean_math_score, na.rm = TRUE),
    ela_sd = sd(mean_ela_score, na.rm = TRUE),
    math_sd = sd(mean_math_score, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

school_scale <- inner_join(nys_schools, scores_std, by="year") %>%
  mutate(
    ela_z_score = (mean_ela_score - ela_mean)/ela_sd,
    math_z_score = (mean_math_score - math_mean)/math_sd)%>%
  select(-c(ela_mean, ela_sd, math_mean, math_sd))

Task 4: Merge datasets

new_df<-merge(nys_acs, nys_schools, by = c("county_name","year"))
new_df

Step 2: Analyze the Data Task 5: Create summary tables 1. For each county: total enrollment, percent of students qualifying for free or reduced price lunch, and percent of population in poverty.

nys_county<-nys_schools%>%
group_by(county_name)%>%
  summarise(total_enroll=sum(total_enroll)
            ,per_free_lunch=sum(per_free_lunch)/sum(total_enroll)
            ,per_reduced_lunch=sum(per_reduced_lunch)/sum(total_enroll)
            ,per_lep=sum(per_lep)/sum(total_enroll)
            ,mean_ela_score=mean(mean_ela_score)
            ,mean_math_score=mean(mean_math_score))
nys_county
  1. For the counties with the top 5 and bottom 5 poverty rate: percent of population in poverty, percent of students qualifying for free or reduced price lunch, mean reading score, and mean math score.
top5_nys_county<-head(nys_county,5)
bottom_5_nys_county<-tail(nys_county,5)
bottom_5_nys_county

Task 6: Data visualization 1. The relationship between access to free/reduced price lunch and test performance, at the school level.

nys_schools %>% 
  group_by(school_name) %>% 
  summarise(per_free_lunch=sum(per_free_lunch)/sum(total_enroll)
            ,per_reduced_lunch=sum(per_reduced_lunch)/sum(total_enroll)
            ,mean_ela_score=mean(mean_ela_score)
            ,mean_math_score=mean(mean_math_score)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=per_free_lunch, y=mean_ela_score,col="green")) + 
  geom_line(aes(x=per_free_lunch, y=mean_math_score,col="yellow")) + 
  geom_line(aes(x=per_reduced_lunch, y=mean_ela_score,col="blue")) + 
  geom_line(aes(x=per_reduced_lunch, y=mean_math_score,col="red")) + 
  labs(title="Test performance by free/reduced lunch", x="free/reduced lunch", y="Test performance")

2.Average test performance across counties with high, low, and medium poverty.

new_df %>% 
  group_by(proverty_level) %>% 
    summarise(
            mean_ela_score=mean(mean_ela_score)
            ,mean_math_score=mean(mean_math_score)) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(aes(x=proverty_level, y=mean_ela_score),col="yellow") + 
  geom_col(aes(x=proverty_level, y=mean_math_score),col="blue") + 
  labs(title="Test performance by county_name", x="proverty_level", y="Test performance")
